Executive Summary
This project focuses on designing, simulating, and analyzing a scalable, secure, and highly available hierarchical campus network. Modeled for a university environment, the infrastructure will establish optimized communication across distinct functional zones—such as administration, faculties, student labs, and centralized server blocks—while enforcing robust perimeter security and enabling secure remote access.
Core Architecture & Features
The implementation follows an industry-standard three-tier hierarchical campus design centered around foundational routing, switching, and security principles:
Segmentation & Switching: Logical isolation of individual departments using dedicated VLANs.
Routing Infrastructure: Multi-subnet inter-VLAN routing combined with OSPF dynamic routing to manage internal traffic paths efficiently.
Access Control & Perimeter Security: Deployment of Access Control Lists (ACLs) to restrict unauthorized lateral movement, alongside secure VPN tunnels for remote connectivity.
External Access: Port Address Translation (NAT/PAT) configured for shared, secure internet access across authorized internal subnets.
Service Validation: Active testing of underlying TCP/UDP protocols via DNS resolution, HTTP web server access, and baseline ICMP reachability.
